Maybe it's all about momentum. 

Losing the momentum for productive (but boring) things. 
Gaining momentum for a new topic. 
Having to lose *that* momentum. 
Getting distracted. 
Then "being distracted" gets its own momentum/activity category. 
Then trying to switch from that...
Sorry to vent, but goddamn is it frustrating to be on your game, and then some distractions throw you off, and now you're just struggling not to go down rabbit-holes. Gah.

So I guess what I'm saying is I'm not gonna believe anybody's "it'll only take a few minutes" line unless I don't need to follow a busy schedule that day. 

All because it's so frustrating to switch gears constantly and feel like nothing of merit is accomplished.

Meanwhile, I'm mad at myself for somehow "losing" 30 minutes that seem unaccounted for, and the stress of a last-minute, surprise task throwing me off my rhythm just fucks with me. 

And then you get all frustrated and just want to say, "fuck it. My day/schedule is shot now."

Maybe it's also due to time blindness, but I know that if somebody says "This'll only take 5 minutes," it will definitely take longer. But for normal people, they can bounce back from "I thought it'd take 5 minutes but it actually took 35."

I've gotten way better at knowing my time limits. As in, "If I talk to this person or read this article for more than 10-15 minutes, it's going to be WAY harder to get back to work/projects/etc." And actually following through with, "I gotta go now or I'll lose my mojo, sorry."

It's like having an impulse that is so fluid, it changes frequently. And if you don't time it to start a thing right when you get that energy to act, it's significantly harder to start. Like all your energy is going to drain before you get to the thing, unless you hit it right.

Sometimes it feels like having ADHD is like a surfer trying to catch a wave just right. If you're too far out and the wave passes you before it crests, you'll have zero motion. If you wait too late, the wave crashes on you with disastrous results.

So yeah. Helping somebody with ADHD? Ask them what they need. Don't just do the whole "you're overthinking it/you're lazy/it's not that hard" trope. It's painful and alienating.

So yeah, a lot of us need grounding, and quiet time to refocus and center. Sometimes that takes a while. Transitions are tough.

So telling us to hurry up, or to "just" go do the next thing, while we're collecting ourselves?

That just adds to those 1000 thoughts. And pressure.

Downside: 1000 thoughts is a lot. All of the time. 

Emotions, stress, unforeseen plan changes, literally any wrench can throw you out of whack. For hours. If you're derailed, suddenly all your thoughts are on the ground. It takes time to recover and pick up those 1000 thoughts.

Sometimes, a few of those 1000 are helpful thoughts that bring up new concepts, or are reminders of things you need to do. And when you're in a good rhythm, you can handle those 1000 thoughts adeptly. Like driving through traffic with a good song.

ADHD is like thinking 1000 thoughts, all at once. Sometimes, that "noise" translates into excess physical energy, or you internalize it and stay calm on the surface while so much is going on mentally.

Like, how many of us can think back to a situation as a kid where we KNOW (and knew then, too!) that we were in the right, but we were never vindicated? 

Imagine teaching your kids that in some cases, their perception was valid and accurate. That's huge prep for adulthood.

I feel like SO many people grew up with parents that were "never wrong," so there's this unrequited yearning for justice on past issues. That frustration can easily carry into adulthood. 

But apologizing to your kids can teach them empathy, forgiveness, and to trust their gut.

Now that I'm thinking of parenting, I have to say I think one of the most important things an adult should demonstrate is how to take accountability for their mistakes, and how to apologize sincerely and with a plan for improvement.

@RunawayScott Exactly. You're still trying to gain a sense of the world, and it's hard to comprehend how different a disabled kid's world is. What I remember most is having a young boy just wail at me, and a teacher came by, said "he wants this toy" and walked away.

@RunawayScott I just assumed it was a common practice. I was in a lot of gifted programs, and these were schools in affluent areas. I have a feeling it was well-intentioned, but without proper staffing, it backfired for a lot of participants.

PS, I know this doesn't paint me in a great light. It's something I still struggle with and fight against, and there's a TON of guilt of not being able/not knowing how to help the kids I was made to interact with. I wish we had proper support back then.

Typically, people fight and advocate for the causes they care about. Could these failed "inclusion programs" have made it harder for kids of the 80s/90s to empathize, and thus advocate for, the disabled community of today?

But it DOES make me wonder

1) if these kinds of programs were widespread in education during the 90s

2) if these programs contributed to the issues facing the disabled community now. As in, are non-disabled people reluctant to help, because of those early negative experiences?

To this day, I have to fight an internalized discomfort with intellectually disabled people. Physically disabled? Zero problems/anxiety. 

I'm sure these early experiences contributed to that discomfort. It makes me mad at the adults in the 90s who didn't know better.

On top of that, in high school, there was a boy my age who would float between cliques on campus. I'm not sure his disorder, but he was highly-functioning. He frequently would cross boundaries with female students, myself included.

I feel guilty saying this, but it was frightening. Being a small young girl, completely clueless as to the expectations on me, trying to interact with somebody who couldn't. And largely unsupervised, for 1-3 hours.

I think I was in 2nd grade? No later than 3rd. My partners were usually unable to speak or move, and often just screamed and flung their arms around while looking at me. 

There'd be like, 3 adults in the classroom of 25 kids, plus the dozen NT buddies brought in.

Random, but was anybody else ever forced to get involved with helping the special education classes at school? 

My elementary school had a buddy system, where NT kids were taken to the special education kids' classroom, assigned a partner, and then told to "hang out."

Woke up late. My dude had already walked and fed the dogs. He greeted me when I came downstairs, took me in his arms and held me, and then offered to paint my nails, something I've missed for months. 

Super super grateful today.

-feeling unsettled if others are working through their own problems

-feeling like you need to maintain others' wellbeing before your own.
